leaves.text: Because there is a lot of mis-information in the media, people can get confused about what a binge really is.
A 'binge' is an episode of overeating.

The technical definition states that the amount of food you eat during the binge needs to be more than another person could eat in the same situation, and that while you are eating you feel as if you have lost control. In reality everyone's experience is different.

Some people don't meet the technical criteria for a binge, they comfort eat - turning to food when they're not hungry to help them deal with stressful situations or feelings. Other people find themselves constantly eating across the day (this is called grazing).

Overeating can take many forms. Just because your pattern of overeating does not sound exactly like a 'binge', does not mean that the skills taught in this package will not help you - in fact, it is likely they will.
MYTH: eating disorders aren't real, they're just a phase that people go through
Eating disorders affect approximately 9% of the Australian population (NEDC, 2013)
It is estimated that 1 in 5 women have an undiagnosed eating disorder (NEDC, 2012b)
It is estimated that the true incidence of bulimia nervosa amongst students and women is 1 in 5 (NEDC, 2012a)
MYTH: eating disorders only affect white, adolescent females
Prevalence of binge eating disorder is almost equal between men and women and affects individuals from a range of cultural and socioeconomic backgrounds (Paxton, 1998)
Although the onset of binge eating is most common in adolescence, it can also appear later in life with many individuals presenting for treatment later in adulthood (APA, 2013)
MYTH: eating disorders are just about food and can be stopped easily
Binge eating is often tied to a complex range of uncomfortable feelings and often leaves the individual feeling hopeless and out of control
Commonly individuals suffering with binge eating will keep their behaviours secret for fear of judgement and shame
Overcoming binge eating cannot be simply achieved by being told to "stop eating" and rather involves exploration of one's eating behaviours and the events or emotions which underlie these behaviours
